related_questions.question: Are hazelnuts good or bad for you?
related_questions.snippet: Hazelnuts are packed with nutrients, including vitamins, minerals, antioxidant compounds and healthy fats. They may also have health benefits, including helping decrease blood fat levels, regulating blood pressure, reducing inflammation and improving blood sugar levels, among others.

related_questions.question: Can you eat hazelnuts raw?
related_questions.snippet: Also known as cobnuts or filberts, hazelnuts are good eaten raw but the flavour takes on a more mellow, sweeter character when they are roasted. Like almost all nuts, they have a high fat content, which means they'll go rancid pretty quickly if not refrigerated.
related_questions.title: Hazelnut - BBC Good Food

related_questions.question: Is A hazelnut a fruit or a nut?
related_questions.snippet: In botany terms, nuts are strictly a particular kind of dry fruit that has a single seed, a hard shell, and a protective husk. Chestnuts, hazelnuts, pecans and walnuts fit the true definition of a nut. Peanuts and almonds do not meet the botanical definition of a true nut.
related_questions.title: Nuts - USDA Forest Service

related_questions.question: Which is healthier almond or hazelnut?
related_questions.snippet: Hazelnuts are rich in monounsaturated fats and vitamin E, while almonds boast high protein content and significant amounts of essential minerals. When directly comparing these nuts, almonds have a slight advantage in terms of protein content, while hazelnuts offer more vitamin E, folate, and magnesium.
related_questions.title: Comparing Hazelnuts and Almonds: Which Nut is Healthier?

answer_box.title: Hazelnut - Wikipedia

hover_info.info: Hazels are plants of the genus Corylus of deciduous trees and large shrubs native to the temperate Northern Hemisphere. The genus is usually placed in the birch family Betulaceae, though some botanists split the hazels (with the hornbeams and allied genera) into a separate family Corylaceae.

buttons.subtitle: Are Hazelnuts Good For You?
buttons.title: Nutritional Benefits of Hazelnuts - Arbor Day Foundation
buttons.snippet: Hazelnuts rank at or near the top of many of the important health categories. Hazelnuts are a rich source of protein, vitamin E, folate, B vitamins, and arginine. In 2003, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved a health claim that linked nut consumption to a reduced risk of heart disease.
snippet_highlighted_words: a rich source of protein, vitamin E, folate, B vitamins, and arginine

buttons.subtitle: How Many Hazelnuts Can I Eat A Day?
buttons.title: How Many Hazelnuts Can You Consume in a Day? - Cookist
buttons.snippet: The recommended daily intake varies slightly between men and women due to differences in nutritional needs. For women, consuming around 20-25 grams of hazelnuts per day is considered beneficial, while men can enjoy up to 30-35 grams. This translates to approximately 15-20 hazelnuts for women and 25-30 for men.
snippet_highlighted_words: 15-20 hazelnuts for women and 25-30 for men

buttons.snippet: How They're Used. Hazelnuts add a delicious flavor to baked goods, including cookies, biscotti, cakes, and tarts. They also go well with savory dishes like seafood, salads, pesto, and even pizza. They're used to flavor liqueur and to make hazelnut butter, a spread similar to peanut butter.

buttons.subtitle: How Many Hazelnuts Should I Eat?
buttons.title: Hazelnuts & Weightloss - Here's What You Need to Know
buttons.snippet: How Many Hazelnuts Should I Eat a Day? The recommended intake of hazelnuts for weight loss is around 1-2 ounces per day. A one-ounce serving of hazelnuts is about 15-20 nuts, but it's best to weigh out your portions if you are trying to track your calories accurately.

buttons.title: Hazelnut Allergen Facts, Symptoms, and Treatment | Allergy Insider
buttons.snippet: If you experience an itchy mouth or ears, scratchy throat, hives on the mouth, or swelling of the lips, mouth, tongue, or throat after eating hazelnuts or other related fresh fruits, raw vegetables, or tree nuts, you may suffer from Pollen Food Allergy Syndrome (PFAS) also called Oral Allergy Syndrome (OAS).
